  the Mississippi River. Jefferson was eager to learn more about the region, especially
  the plants, animals, and people {-(that/which)+that|311} lived there. \\r\\n\\r\\nLewis,
  Clark, and the rest of their expedition, {-(that/which)+which|311} was often called
  the Corps of Discovery, left {-(st. louis, Missouri/St. Louis, Missouri)+St. Louis,
  Missouri|496}in May of 1804. Throughout the trip, Lewis kept a journal {-(when/where)+where|314}
  he recorded details about the plants and animals that he encountered. As they traveled,
  the expedition had many unique experiences. They faced obstacles and challenges
  along the way, such as bad weather and illness, but also received help from the
  native people that they encountered.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe {-(corps of discovery/Corps of Discovery)+Corps
  of Discovery|496} reached the Pacific Ocean in November of 1805. They spent the
  winter in a homemade fort in present-day {-(Oregon./oregon.)+Oregon.|496} Throughout
  the winter, they faced many dangers, including a conflict with the local Blackfeet
  Indians. There was also an accident where Lewis was shot in the thigh by one of
  his own men while he was {-(hunted./hunting.)+hunting.|318} The Corps of Discovery
  eventually traveled back to St. Louis, Missouri to share their findings. They changed
  the face of the {-(United States/united states)+United States|496} by returning
