', 11, NULL, 'A sentence may consist of more than one subject or predicate. A compound subject refers to two or more simple subjects that share the same predicate -- for instance, in the sentence “Jack and Jill use Quill,” the compound subject is “Jack and Jill.” A compound predicate refers to two or more simple predicates (or verbs) that share the same subject -- for instance, in the sentence “The comedian surprised and entertained the crowd,” the  compound predicate is “surprised and entertained.” Needless to say, these aren’t the only examples of this important concept!

This Complex Sentences pack is designed to introduce students to the concept of compound subjects, objects, and predicates by guiding them to combine sentences and analyze relationships.

In this pack, which consists of four activities, students will gain practice in determining the relationship between ideas and the construction of a grammatically stronger, more well-structured sentence.

The four activities altogether contain 31 items. The pack is expected to take roughly 60 minutes.
', NULL, NULL);
